{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622438"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:02:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:02:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16798"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16798"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67274"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9489"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16798"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52726"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5160"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22428"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67274"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a generalised tonic-clonic seizure. She is administered intravenous diazepam which successfully terminates the seizure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of benzodiazepines?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Directly opens chloride channels","Enhances GABA binding","Inhibits GABA breakdown","Increases GABA synthesis","Blocks glutamate receptors"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBenzodiazepines work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eenhancing GABA binding \u003C/strong\u003Eto GABA-A receptors. They bind to a specific site on the GABA-A receptor complex, which allosterically modifies the receptor to increase the frequency of chloride channel opening when GABA binds. This leads to increased inhibitory neurotransmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBenzodiazepines require GABA to be present for their effect, and cannot \u003Cstrong\u003Edirectly open chloride channels.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBenzodiazepines have no effect on the production of GABA in neurons and therefore cannot \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease GABA synthesis.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that benzodiazepines \u003Cstrong\u003Eblock glutamate receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; they do not interact with the glutamate neurotransmitter system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBenzodiazepines do not affect the metabolic processes involving GABA and do not have a role in \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting GABA breakdown.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe enhanced inhibitory effect of GABA results in anxiolysis, sedation, muscle relaxation, and anticonvulsant effects, which explains the therapeutic uses of benzodiazepines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Benzodiazepines enhance the effect of gamma-aminobutyric acid by binding to a specific site on GABA-A receptors.","GABA-A receptor activation increases chloride ion conductance, leading to neuronal hyperpolarisation.","Benzodiazepines do not directly open chloride channels but rather potentiate GABA\u0027s natural inhibitory effect."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52726"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16798"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52726"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T12:25:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T12:26:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9489"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67274"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type